prestigious John Kluge Fellowship

00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:17.140
to pursue her research
here at the Library.

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:19.870
Now, one of the great things about
receiving a Kluge fellowship is

00:02:19.870 --> 00:02:23.170
that the award allows scholars
from throughout the United States,

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:25.490
really, throughout the
world, to come to the Library

00:02:25.490 --> 00:02:27.440
to pursue their research at this,

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:30.500
the world's largest research
facility, and to take advantage

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:34.260
of the strength and resources of
the Library's numerous collections.

00:02:34.260 --> 00:02:37.610
At the American Folklife Center
where Dr. Kaskowitz has chosen

00:02:37.610 --> 00:02:41.710
for so much of her research
during her residency,

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:47.070
AFC is one of 20 specialized
reading rooms here at the Library.

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:49.790
By itself alone, the American
Folklife Center is the world's

00:02:49.790 --> 00:02:51.780
largest ethnographic collection.

00:02:51.780 --> 00:02:55.460
We think we have over six million
items documenting various aspects

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:59.210
of traditional cultures
from more than 144 nations

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:02.490
and over 800 cultural groups.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:04.710
Our greatest strengths
is, of course,

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:07.440
our holdings in American culture,
and especially American music.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:11.490
We have more than 3,000
individual collections

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:13.880
at the American Folklife
Center, and there are many

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:16.090 position:56%
that have never been fully explored.

00:03:16.090 --> 00:03:17.810
Among these -- and I should add one

00:03:17.810 --> 00:03:21.490
of the staff's favorite is a
collection of Sidney Robertson,

00:03:21.490 --> 00:03:24.740
or she was known for her
marriage, Sidney Robertson Cowell,

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:29.310
which we split between our holdings
and the Music Division holding.

00:03:29.310 --> 00:03:33.640 position:56%
Robertson was a pioneering collector
whose significant contributions

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:35.710
to the field of folklore

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:39.650
and ethnomusicology have long been
overshadowed by her contemporaries,

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:42.420
like Alan Lomax and Charles Seeger.

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:45.960
Therefore, as happy as we
are to welcome Kluge fellows,

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:48.150
we were particularly
delighted when Sheryl arrived

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:51.480
to research Robertson's
rich collection.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:53.460
And I should add, I just
want to give a shout-out

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:57.220
to AFC staff member, Kathy Kurtz
[phonetic], who is here today

00:03:57.220 --> 00:04:01.320
who has also done significant
work on Sidney Robertson Cowell.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:05.770
And but there was more than
enough material for many scholars,

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:07.710
and both Sheryl and
Kathy spent a lot

00:04:07.710 --> 00:04:10.810
of time comparing notes
and working together.

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:15.640
So Sheryl Kaskowitz received her
PhD in music and ethnomusicology --

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:19.330
well actually it's in music with
a focus on ethnomusicology, right,

00:04:19.330 --> 00:04:22.630
from Harvard University in 2011.

00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:25.990
And she's now at Brown
University as a researcher,

00:04:25.990 --> 00:04:29.380
as well as an independent
scholar in Rhode Island.

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:32.370
Her research interests
focus on popular vernacular

00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:38.580
and participatory music making in
the US, and include both historical

00:04:38.580 --> 00:04:40.360
and contemporary practices.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:43.580
Her most recent book, "God Bless
America," which was published

00:04:43.580 --> 00:04:48.030
by Oxford University Press in
2013, presents a social history

00:04:48.030 --> 00:04:52.460
and an ethnography of the
iconic Irving Berlin song.

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:55.920
Today, she will be presenting an
overview of her current research,

00:04:55.920 --> 00:05:01.750
and I'd like to ask you to
join me in welcoming her

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:05.340
for this presentation
entitled, "Delight in What it is

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:12.510
to be an American: Sidney Robertson
on the Road, 1935 to 1937."

